WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:05.565
Pneumonia is an infection of the lung
parenchyma that fills the alveoli with inflammatory

2
00:00:05.565 --> 00:00:07.304
fluid, cells, and debris.

3
00:00:07.985 --> 00:00:11.385
For respiratory therapists, this is not
just an infection problem,

4
00:00:11.465 --> 00:00:14.784
it is a gas exchange and airway clearance
problem.

5
00:00:15.484 --> 00:00:19.305
Normally, alveoli are filled with air and
allow oxygen to

6
00:00:19.305 --> 00:00:20.165
move into the bloodstream.

7
00:00:20.725 --> 00:00:24.145
In pneumonia, those alveoli fill with
fluid instead.

8
00:00:24.524 --> 00:00:27.625
This reduces ventilation, while perfusion
may continue,

9
00:00:28.184 --> 00:00:30.344
creating a ventilation-perfusion mismatch.

10
00:00:31.024 --> 00:00:34.005
In severe cases, this becomes shunt-like
physiology,

11
00:00:34.424 --> 00:00:35.485
leading to hypoxemia.

12
00:00:36.284 --> 00:00:38.465
Clinically, patients often present with
fever,

13
00:00:39.104 --> 00:00:41.084
cough, sputum production, dyspnea,

14
00:00:41.404 --> 00:00:42.544
and pleuritic chest pain.

15
00:00:43.044 --> 00:00:44.924
On assessment, you may hear crackles,

16
00:00:45.505 --> 00:00:46.865
bronchial breath sounds, or ronchi.

17
00:00:47.465 --> 00:00:50.444
You may also see tachypnea, increased work
of breathing,

18
00:00:50.584 --> 00:00:52.284
and decreased oxygen saturation.

19
00:00:53.025 --> 00:00:55.584
Early in the disease, patients may
hyperventilate,

20
00:00:55.805 --> 00:00:57.325
causing a low PaCO2.

21
00:00:57.784 --> 00:01:00.505
But as fatigue sets in, PaCO2 can rise.

22
00:01:01.064 --> 00:01:02.305
This is a critical transition.

23
00:01:03.145 --> 00:01:08.105
A rising PaCO2 with worsening mental
status is a major red flag for ventilatory

24
00:01:08.105 --> 00:01:08.525
failure.

25
00:01:09.444 --> 00:01:13.364
Diagnostics typically include a chest
x-ray showing infiltrates or consolidation,

26
00:01:14.004 --> 00:01:16.944
along with ABG analysis and oxygenation
monitoring.

27
00:01:17.745 --> 00:01:21.065
Sputum may be present, and may require
RT-assisted collection.

28
00:01:21.504 --> 00:01:25.025
There are different types of pneumonia,
including community-acquired,

29
00:01:25.565 --> 00:01:29.224
hospital-acquired, ventilator-associated,
aspiration,

30
00:01:29.385 --> 00:01:30.625
and opportunistic.

31
00:01:31.165 --> 00:01:35.404
Recognizing the type helps predict
severity and guide management priorities.

32
00:01:36.084 --> 00:01:39.785
From an RT perspective, your priorities
include assessing oxygenation,

33
00:01:40.125 --> 00:01:42.985
ventilation, work of breathing, breath
sounds,

34
00:01:43.144 --> 00:01:44.125
and secretion burden.

35
00:01:44.745 --> 00:01:48.705
You must determine if the patient can
maintain oxygenation, ventilate

36
00:01:48.705 --> 00:01:51.764
effectively, clear secretions, and protect
their

37
00:01:51.764 --> 00:01:52.025
airway.

38
00:01:52.964 --> 00:01:56.584
Management may include oxygen therapy,
escalation to high-flow nasal

39
00:01:56.584 --> 00:02:00.385
cannula or non-invasive support, and in
severe cases,

40
00:02:00.985 --> 00:02:02.705
intubation and mechanical ventilation.

41
00:02:03.745 --> 00:02:07.065
Airway clearance is also key, especially
in patients with weak

42
00:02:07.065 --> 00:02:08.964
cough or excessive secretions.

43
00:02:09.664 --> 00:02:13.664
Red flags include refractory hypoxemia,
rising CO2,

44
00:02:14.345 --> 00:02:17.464
altered mental status, hypotension, and
inability

45
00:02:17.464 --> 00:02:18.524
to clear secretions.

46
00:02:18.945 --> 00:02:21.705
These patients require immediate
escalation.

47
00:02:22.464 --> 00:02:23.785
The key takeaway is this.

48
00:02:24.365 --> 00:02:27.425
Pneumonia becomes dangerous when the
patient can no longer oxygenate,

49
00:02:27.785 --> 00:02:29.324
ventilate, or protect their airway.

50
00:02:29.824 --> 00:02:32.485
As an RT, your job is to recognize that
transition

51
00:02:32.485 --> 00:02:34.085
early and act quickly.

